The Relationship of Crime with House Prices in the State of Maryland

By Paul Makarevich

Introduction: Why are we observing this data?

The purpose of this project is to study the effect of crime on house prices in Maryland while observing a typical data science pipeline (how to study, interpret, and use a dataset from start to finish). As a potential future homebuyer, I have heard so much talk about the crazy housing market, and also how location matters above everything, especially in crowded areas. I have heard it said that one of the factors that affects the prices at a location is crime, but I wanted to see how much crime can affect these prices, and whether or not we could use it in order to predict changes in housing prices. I also want to see if specific crimes have a greater effect than other ones. I have included inflation data to account for inflation, so that there is some normalization of price data.

Summary question: Is there a relationship between crime rates and house prices in the different municipalities in Maryland?

Data Curation

Information on Datsets¶

I will be using the following datasets:

https://opendata.maryland.gov/Business-and-Economy/Maryland-Real-Property-Assessments_Hidden-Property/ed4q-f8tm/about_data
This is all of the real estate sales in Maryland for the past years from the Maryland state government.

https://opendata.maryland.gov/Public-Safety/Violent-Crime-Property-Crime-by-Municipality-2000-/2p5g-xrcb/about_data
This is all of the crime data in Maryland by municipality for the past 34 years from the Maryland state government.

https://opendata.maryland.gov/Public-Safety/Violent-Crime-Property-Crime-by-County-1975-to-Pre/jwfa-fdxs/about_data
This is all of the crime data in Maryland by county since 1975 from the Maryland state government.

The following two sources are to fill gaps in the data. See Data Cleaning section. https://mdsp.maryland.gov/Pages/Documents,%20Forms,%20Publications,%20and%20Proactive%20Releases.aspx
2022 Maryland Uniform Crime Report
https://msa.maryland.gov/msa/mdmanual/01glance/html/pop.html
Population by County in Maryland (Census data)

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/pavankrishnanarne/us-inflation-dataset-1947-present
This is the inflation data (Consumer Price Index) in the United States since 1947.

As we can see, some of the cities listed in the estate dataset are not in the crime dataset. Therefore, we will try to replace the jurisdiction data with the county data in this case. We will also grab the county name column from the dataset.

In [8]:
needed_columns.append("County Name (MDP Field: CNTYNAME)")

Another thing that we have to consider is when the property was assessed. How do we know that? Well, after some research on it: https://dat.maryland.gov/realproperty/Pages/HomeOwners-Guide.aspx, in Maryland, properties are assessed once every three years in cycles. Therefore, we need to grab the date assessed in order to know when theses assessments happened.

In [9]:
needed_columns.append("CURRENT CYCLE DATA: Date Assessed (YYYY.MM) (MDP Field: LASTASSD. SDAT Field #169)")

Let's get rid of some of the columns that we don't need. It seems that PRIOR ASSESSMENT YEAR 3 Total Assessment (#181), has all null values. We will get rid of the column. Further, let's wipe the grantor deed reference, transfer number, for now, as we don't need that for our analysis.

In [11]:
for column in estate_clean_df.columns.to_list():
    if "grantor" in column.lower():
        needed_columns.remove(column)
    if "transfer number" in column.lower():
        needed_columns.remove(column)
    if "land" in column.lower():
        needed_columns.remove(column)
    if "improvement" in column.lower():
        needed_columns.remove(column)
    if "mortgage" in column.lower():
        needed_columns.remove(column)

Ok, now we are ready for our final real estate dataset. What we care about is the year of the evaluation/sale/price of the property from one evaluation/sale/price to the next. The final dataset is going to be measuring one price to the next with the year of sale from that price to the next. We will grab the values that we need and put them into a dictionary with lists for each column (in order), so that we can create a final dataframe from the dictionary, suited to our needs.

In [33]:
# This function takes in the individual values for a datapoint, and essentially creates a row of the dataframe with the values.
def reconstruct_dataframe(reconstructed_dict, city, county, date1, date2, price, final_price):
    # We will also turn all of the cities into camel case while we have easy access to this raw data
    city_word_list = city.split(" ")
    my_city_string=""
    for word in city_word_list:
        if (word !=""):
            my_city_string=word[0].upper()+word[1:].lower()+ " "
    my_city_string=my_city_string[:-1]
    reconstructed_dict["City"].append(my_city_string)
    reconstructed_dict["County"].append(county)
    reconstructed_dict["Date_1"].append(date1)
    reconstructed_dict["Date_2"].append(date2)
    reconstructed_dict["Price"].append(price)
    reconstructed_dict["Final_Price"].append(final_price)

# Create a blank dictionary, and put blank lists for each field (column)
reconstructed_dict={}
reconstructed_dict["City"]=[]
reconstructed_dict["County"]=[]
reconstructed_dict["Date_1"]=[]
reconstructed_dict["Date_2"]=[]
reconstructed_dict["Price"]=[]
reconstructed_dict["Final_Price"]=[]

# Number of rows in new dataframe so far
count=0

# Loop through the dataframe
for index in range(0,len(estate_clean_df_dict["Current_Assessment_Date"])):

    # Add the city and county for every new row
    city=estate_clean_df_dict["City"][index]
    county=estate_clean_df_dict["County"][index]

    """ Explanation of if logic:
            The most recent sale is always going to be in Sale_1_Date. The second most recent in Sale_2. The third most recent in Sale_3.
            If Sale_1 is not null, check Sale_2. If Sale_2 is not null, check Sale_3. Then, add the sales in order to the dictionary.
            Finally, add a row that will be from the last assessment to the current assessment, which should always be valid (based on our cleaning).
    """
    
    if (estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Date"][index]!="0000.00.00"):
        if (estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_2_Date"][index]!="0000.00.00"):
            reconstruct_dataframe(reconstructed_dict,city,county,estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_2_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_2_Price"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Price"][index])
            count=count+1
            if (estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_3_Date"][index]!="0000.00.00"):
                reconstruct_dataframe(reconstructed_dict,city,county,estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_3_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_2_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_3_Price"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_2_Price"][index])
                count=count+1 

            # Make sure that if the most recent sale is after the last assessment, that the order is correct
            elif (estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Date"][index]>estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment_Date"][index]):
                    reconstruct_dataframe(reconstructed_dict,city,county,estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Price"][index])
            else:
                reconstruct_dataframe(reconstructed_dict,city,county,estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Price"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment"][index])
                count=count+1
        # Make sure that if the most recent sale is after the last assessment, that the order is correct
        elif (estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Date"][index]>estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment_Date"][index]):
                    reconstruct_dataframe(reconstructed_dict,city,county,estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Price"][index])
        else:
            reconstruct_dataframe(reconstructed_dict,city,county,estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Sale_1_Price"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment"][index])
            count=count+1

    reconstruct_dataframe(reconstructed_dict,city,county,estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Current_Assessment_Date"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Last_Assessment"][index],estate_clean_df_dict["Current_Assessment"][index])
    count=count+1

Notice that violent crime and property crime percent are inversely proportional. Therefore, we can get rid of one of them because having two of essentially same features in a model is not helpful. We will get rid of these later.

I wonder if different jurisdictions within a county have significantly different crime rates. This is important for us to know because we currently plan to check crime rates based on the jurisdiction and not county (unless we cannot find the jurisdiction in the housing dataset).

We will thus perform a hypothesis test to check the statistical significance. Note our alpha value is .05, which means we want it to be so that when samples of this size are taken, at most 5% of the time, if the null hypothesis were true, the values would fall into this range. Such a low percentage allows us to reject the null hypothesis.

Hypothesis Test for Crime Data¶

H0 (null): There is no statistical difference in crime rates between jurisdictions and the general county

Ha (alternative): There is a statistical difference in crime rates between jurisdictions and the general county

alpha=.05

We will be using a one-sample t-test as we have one variable, and we are comparing to a known population mean.

According to our test, Dorchester, Caroline, Washington, Anne Arundel, Allegany, Montgomery, Prince George's, Kent, Frederick, Cecil, Wicomico, Talbot, Charles, Calvert, Somerset, St. Mary's, and Carroll counties all have significant differences between the jurisdictions and the county mean for crime rates according to their p-value which is less than the alpha value of .05. This means that when samples of this size are taken, if the null hypothesis were true, the values would fall into this range less than 5% of the time. This means that for these counties, we reject the null hypothesis as it has a very low likelihood of being true. We propose that for these aforementioned counties there is a statistical difference in crime rates between jurisdictions and the general county.

According to our test, Harford, Worcester, Garrett, Baltimore City, Baltimore, Howard, Worcester, Queen Anne's, and counties all do NOT have significant differences between the jursdictions and the county mean for crime rates according to their p-value which is greater than the alpha value of .05. We therefore do not reject the null hypothesis for these counties. This means that when samples of this size are taken, if the null hypothesis were true, the values would fall into this range more than 5% of the time. This means that for these counties, we fail to reject the null hypothesis as it has a fairly large likelihood that it could be true. We propose that for the aforementioned counties there is no statistical difference in crime rates between jurisdictions and the general county.

Exploring home prices by county (over the years)¶

Ok, now let's look at home prices by county. We will create a barplot to view several statistical measures within the data.

In [61]:

Ok, so there are a lot of things going on with this plot. We can clearly see that every category has a huuuuuuge amount of outliers. Some of these outliers range into the hundreds of millions. Obviously, no home costs 900 million (which is one of the outliers, when you do the max function), so we will have to look at these outliers and identify which ones that we will keep.

How is an outlier defined in this case, and how do we even read a box and whisker plot? Well, the line that we see in the middle of each box defines where the median value in the set of values is. So for example, the median value (or value at the 50% mark, when arranging the values in order) is about 290,000. The edges of the green box mark the 25% of values and 75% values respectfully. So for the bottom line, 25% of all values would have a value at or below that one. For the top line, 75% of all values would have a value at or below that one. For the lines that shoot out of the box, those mark values that are not within this 25-75% range, but are not considered outliers. Usually, the values that are considered outliers are above or below the edges of the box and go out by an additional amount that is the the difference between the 25 and 75% mark, multiplied by 1.5 (called the interquartile range, multiplied by 1.5). We can see that above this 1.5*interquartile_range above the 75% mark (called the upper fence), there are a lot of values. This dataset has a lot of outliers in every single county. We need to come up with a way to deal with them so that way we can still build a useful model, as they will throw off the data.

Thankfully, however, we do not have any outliers below the box, so we only need to deal with values that are extremely high. I will likely filter out some of these outliers based on some sort of upper-value threshhold--especially because they are likely part of a multi-home deal. We want to be able to predict the change in the house prices, and we can't track the changes of multi-home deals.

So, what have we observed with our three statistical methods:¶

By observing the differences in the crime data and how most counties vary significantly in their crime data by jurisdiction, we know that our jurisdiction data is important, and that we shouldn't ignore it. This is important for us to know while building our model.

By observing the differences in the median between counties, we understand that different counties sell houses for different values, in general, and we vary in price by county. Further, we see that we have a lot of outliers with extreme house prices. We now know that we have to devise a way to deal with these outliers before starting our machine learning.

By observing the correlation between different crimes and house prices, we can see which crime data points have a high correlation with each other, and which crime data points have a correlation with the price. We now understand the importance of non-linear prediction, and know that we can remove some of the extra features in the crime dataset that are highly correlated. Finally, we understand that the breaking and entering crime data is likely the most important.

We are now ready to prepare for machine learning.

Machine Learning (prediction)

It is finally time for machine learning. We will now combine our datasets, keep certain features based on what we need, and normalize price data based on inflation.

Final Pre-Processing¶

First, we will get rid of our outliers in the real estate data. We will use the standard definition of outliers (upper fence). See Exploring home prices by county (over the years) in the Data Exploration section if you want more information on what upper fence means. Also see https://www.statology.org/upper-and-lower-fences/.

But first, we will get rid of 0-values in the price. They will skew our data. No real esatate is worth 0 dollars.

In [66]:
final_estate_df = final_estate_df[final_estate_df["Price"]!=0.0]
final_estate_df = final_estate_df[final_estate_df["Final_Price"]!=0.0]

Now we will adjust prices for inflation. We are adjusting before getting rid of outliers because the adjustment will affect which points are considered outliers, as some of the upper outliers will disappear once adjusted for crazy inflation. (1 million dollars for a home in 2024 is the same as 262 thousand dollars in 1980).

First, let's account for inflation in our price data. In order for this adjustment, we will create a list of inflation adjusted data and then add it back to the dataframe.

In [67]:
# We are making the date the index, and then we are creating a dictionary where the keys are the date, and the values are the inflation index.
inflation_dictionary = final_inflation_df.set_index("Date").to_dict()
inflation_dictionary = inflation_dictionary['Inflation_Index']

# Missing value, taking from https://www.usinflationcalculator.com/inflation/consumer-price-index-and-annual-percent-changes-from-1913-to-2008/
inflation_dictionary['2024']=308

# Create the necessary lists in order to make the new columns
my_inflated_values_price=[]
my_inflated_values_final_price=[]
my_price = final_estate_df["Price"].to_list()
my_final_price = final_estate_df["Final_Price"].to_list()

# Loop through the dataframe, going through the dates of the 'price' feature
for index, date in enumerate(final_estate_df["Date_1"].to_list()):
    if (str(date) not in inflation_dictionary.keys()):
        my_inflated_values_price.append(0.0)
    else:
        my_inflated_values_price.append(my_price[index]/inflation_dictionary[str(date)])

# Loop through the dataframe, going through the dates of the 'final_price' feature
for index, date in enumerate(final_estate_df["Date_2"].to_list()):
    # If there is a date that is outside the scope of 1947-2024, it should be removed
    if (str(date) not in inflation_dictionary.keys()):
        my_inflated_values_final_price.append(0.0)
    else:
        my_inflated_values_final_price.append(my_final_price[index]/inflation_dictionary[str(date)])

final_estate_df["Price"]=my_inflated_values_price
final_estate_df["Final_Price"]=my_inflated_values_final_price
final_estate_df = final_estate_df[final_estate_df["Price"]!=0.0]
final_estate_df = final_estate_df[final_estate_df["Final_Price"]!=0.0]

Now that we have adjusted for inflation, let's take the upper fence and take away all outliers above it. We do not need our model to be greatly skewed by a billion dollar deal on multiple homes.

Splitting and Normalizing the Data¶

We will be using the train_test_split function and StandardScaler from the scikit-learn package. The train_test_split function splits the data into training and testing sets. We split data into training and testing sets so that we can see if our model will work on data that it has never seen before (test set). We will be using 20% of our data for our testing.

In [82]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
features = scaler.fit_transform(final_df.loc[:,final_df.columns != "Final_Price"])
answer = final_df["Final_Price"]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, answer, test_size=0.20)

# PyTorch only accepts tensors, so let's change the type of our data to PyTorch tensors
X_train = torch.tensor(X_train, dtype=torch.float32)
y_train = torch.tensor(y_train.values, dtype=torch.float32).reshape(-1,1)
X_test = torch.tensor(X_test, dtype=torch.float32)
y_test = torch.tensor(y_test.values, dtype=torch.float32).reshape(-1,1)

Building and Training the Model¶

We will be using PyTorch for our machine learning. And yes, call me old-fashioned, but I will be tuning the loss functions and the model architecture by hand. (We went from a loss of .001 to .000006, tried and removed a dropout layer, changed the batch size, changed the number of neurons, etc.; hyper-parameter tuning). I did not use any grid-search methods because I have experience looking at loss-curves and playing around with machine learning models. Others may want to use grid-search: a method for changing parameters one by one in which the program decides which ones are going to be most effective before training every model fully so that a good model is built and with the right parameters. Note we are using mean absolute error as a loss measurement (average absolute difference between the prediction and the actual value).

In [83]:
my_model = torch.nn.Sequential(
  # We start with 13 feature columns, so that's why we start with 13 nodes
  torch.nn.Linear(in_features=13, out_features=26),
  torch.nn.LeakyReLU(), # we are going to use the leaky version because it prevents vanishing gradients
  torch.nn.Linear(in_features=26, out_features=50),
  torch.nn.LeakyReLU(),
  torch.nn.Linear(in_features=50, out_features=24),
  torch.nn.LeakyReLU(),
  torch.nn.Linear(in_features=24, out_features=15),
  torch.nn.LeakyReLU(),
  torch.nn.Linear(in_features=15, out_features=1)
)

learning_rate=.000006

# Use mean absolute error
my_mae = torch.nn.L1Loss()

# We will be using the Adam optimizer (commonly used)
my_optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(my_model.parameters(),lr=learning_rate)
epochs = 20
my_batch_size = 128

# Used to save the losses at different points so we can graph it
save_loss=[]

# Model training
my_model.train()
for epoch in range(epochs):
  for number in range(0,len(X_train), my_batch_size):
    # Predict for batch
    prediction = my_model(X_train[number:(number+my_batch_size)])
    # Get the actual values for batch
    actual = y_train[number:(number+my_batch_size)]

    # Calculate loss for batch
    loss = my_mae(prediction,actual)

    # Clear old gradients
    my_optimizer.zero_grad()

    # Calculate gradients
    loss.backward()

    # Save current loss
    save_loss.append(loss.item())

    # Optimize (perform gradient descent) based on batch
    my_optimizer.step()

  # Print loss at end of epoch
  print("Loss for epoch " +str(epoch+1)+ ": "+str(loss.item()))

As we can see, there are clearly some points that have a vastly different value than expected, but such is the world of real-estate. Although we still have a fairly large difference in accuracy for the test data, we recognize that the mean absolute error is an average (mean) of the error. That means that when there are large differences in the data (say a disaster takes out a house), this event gets factored into the accuracy.

Something to notice about our visual is that we have some very, very good predictions that are almost right on the money. It seems that in general, our model can successfully predict the movement of house prices with crime data pretty well in a standard case. Let's see if it works on some real-world data. Insights and Conclusions

When we started off this document, we asked the question: Is there a relationship between crime rates and house prices in different municipalities in the state of Maryland?

Based on our data analysis, and our machine learning, we can say that yes, there is some sort of relationship between crime rates and house prices based on municipality. We have observed this with tests, charts, and analysis.

There are, however, several lessons that can be learned:

  1. Any sort of trends we see are very general--- For further analysis, it would be much better to look at neighborhood crime. However, this data does not seem to be publicly available. If I were a rich man (no, this isn't Fiddler on the Roof), I would definitely buy this data from the several crime watch websites that are out there. Some great examples of differences between neighborhoods can be seen in Baltimore. You can go a few blocks in the wrong direction and end up in a neighborhood with a vastly different crime rate. If you're a Baltimorean, think Canton vs. West Baltimore. If you've been in College Park, well... you know what areas to avoid. The difference is stark, and scary.
  2. Data preparation and exploration is much more than half the work. Take time to make sure that it is done right so that your model ends up being trainable, and actually helps to provide some sort of insights.
  3. Certain crimes are more correlated to house prices. The higher the breaking and entering percentage, the lower the price of the home, in general. This makes sense because no one wants their house broken into! But note that correlation is not causation (see readings).
  4. There is a huuuge difference in house prices between counties. According to the bar chart, 75% of homes in Allegany County cost less than the cheapest 25% of Howard County. There is a stark difference between the two, and it just shows that location matters a lot for house prices.
  5. Our model doesn't really say much, as we do not have enough input data to predict the true price of a home. As you might expect, a lot can change inside of a home in 20 years. We can only observe very general trends (reiterating).

Thank you for letting me take you on a data science and analytics journey.
